snippet.textDisplay:
You guys used what is essentially a portrait mode on a composition that sort of demands being able to see bright, colorful details in the distance. The last one should've been a portrait of a human, or maybe something else adding 'importance' to what's in the foreground.

When people look at a photo with no theme or meaning, and lots of details popping, they want to be be able to see the details. When trying to see those details and focus on them and encountered with blurriness instead, people get annoyed.

snippet.textDisplay:
Well soft background doesn't make a better photo always. Portraits with softer/blurry background looks good. But when you are taking a photo of something that has lots of details and you use shallow depth of field, it's simply a bad photo. That's what happened in 2nd round. The photo have lots of informations, like the car, the color chart, the hands, shoes, green chair. Simply the camera should have had higher f stop or deeper depth of field.
Remember beauty lies in the eyes of the beholder. It's true for photographs as well. There's no hard and fast rule for it.

Or, if instead, you put a stapler in place of the Rubik's cube....people would have preferred it blurred.
